---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";

// Tool metadata
const name = "Double Click Test";
const category = "display";
const tier = "Display & Input Diagnostics";

// On-page SEO metadata
const pageTitle = "Double Click Test - Free Online Mouse Double Click Tester";
const description = "Free double click test online. Run a mouse double click test to detect switch chatter, check double clicking on a single click, and use as a double click tester with real-time diagnostics.";
const canonicalUrl = "https://boardtools.app/tools/display/double-click";
const ogImage = "/og/double-click.png";
const keywords = "double click test, mouse double click test, keyboard double click test, double click test mouse, double click test online, mouse double click test website, double click, how to double click on mac, double click tester, how to double click, mouse chatter test, mouse button tester";
---

<Layout
  title={pageTitle}
  description={description}
  toolName={name}
  toolCategory={category}
  keywords={keywords}
  canonical={canonicalUrl}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  ogType="website"
  hideBanner={true}
>
  <!-- SEO JSON-LD WebApplication Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "WebApplication",
      "name": "Double Click Test",
      "alternateName": "Mouse Double Click Tester & Switch Chatter Detector",
      "url": "https://boardtools.app/tools/display/double-click",
      "description": "Free online double click test to check your mouse for switch chatter and double clicking on a single click. Measure click intervals in milliseconds and verify hardware reliability.",
      "applicationCategory": "DeveloperApplication",
      "operatingSystem": "All",
      "browserRequirements": "Requires JavaScript. Requires Mouse input.",
      "featureList": [
        "Real-time click interval calculation in milliseconds",
        "Adjustable hardware switch chatter threshold (5ms - 150ms)",
        "Separate button diagnostics (Left, Middle, Right)",
        "Satisfying visual ripple feedback and shake animations on chatter",
        "Detailed session statistics and CSV data export",
        "Click speed rhythm practice secondary mode",
        "100% private client-side execution"
      ],
      "offers": {
        "@type": "Offer",
        "price": "0.00",
        "priceCurrency": "USD"
      }
    }
  </script>

  <!-- Breadcrumb Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
      "itemListElement": [
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 1,
          "name": "Home",
          "item": "https://boardtools.app/"
        },
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 2,
          "name": "Tools",
          "item": "https://boardtools.app/tools"
        },
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 3,
          "name": "Display",
          "item": "https://boardtools.app/tools/display"
        },
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 4,
          "name": "Double Click Test",
          "item": "https://boardtools.app/tools/display/double-click"
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

  <!-- FAQ JSON-LD Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to test mouse double click?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>To test your mouse double click, open this double click test tool and click inside the test area with the button you want to check. The tool measures the millisecond interval between each click and flags any that arrive faster than the chatter threshold. If a single physical press registers two clicks in under 50&ndash;80ms, the tool marks it as chatter, which indicates a failing switch. Run 30&ndash;50 clicks per button to get a reliable reading in the session summary.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to double click on Mac?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>On a Mac, double click by pressing the trackpad or mouse button twice in quick succession without moving the pointer. On a MacBook trackpad you can also enable \"Tap to Click\" in System Settings &gt; Trackpad, then tap twice. You can adjust how fast the two clicks must be by changing the double-click speed under System Settings &gt; Accessibility &gt; Pointer Control (or Mouse/Trackpad). A slower speed gives you more time between the two clicks.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why is my double click not working?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A double click may fail for several reasons: the double-click speed in your operating system is set too fast, the mouse switch is worn out, the surface is dirty, or a driver is malfunctioning. Try slowing the double-click speed in your mouse settings, cleaning the mouse, testing on another USB port, or trying a different mouse. Running this double click test helps confirm whether the button is registering clicks at all.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to double click?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>To double click, quickly press and release the left mouse button twice in a row while keeping the pointer still. Both clicks must land within your system's double-click time window (usually around 500ms) for it to count as a double click rather than two separate single clicks. If you find double clicking difficult, increase the double-click time in your operating system's mouse settings.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why is my mouse double clicking on a single click?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A mouse that double clicks on a single press is almost always suffering from switch chatter. As a mechanical switch ages, its metal contact loses tension or collects debris and bounces when pressed, sending two signals instead of one. This tool detects that by measuring the interval between clicks: intervals under 50ms during a single press strongly suggest hardware chatter. The fix is usually replacing or cleaning the switch, or replacing the mouse.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is double click?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A double click is the action of pressing a mouse button twice in rapid succession, within a short time window, to trigger a command such as opening a file, folder, or application. The operating system treats two quick clicks as a single double-click event, distinct from two separate single clicks. The maximum gap allowed between the two presses is controlled by your double-click speed setting.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to double click on Chromebook?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>On a Chromebook touchpad, double click by tapping the touchpad twice quickly with one finger, or by pressing down on the pad twice. If tapping is disabled, enable \"Tap-to-click\" in Settings &gt; Device &gt; Touchpad. With an external mouse, simply press the left button twice in quick succession. You can also adjust touchpad speed in the same settings menu if double clicks are not registering reliably.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why isn't my double click working?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>If your double click isn't working, the most common causes are a double-click speed set too fast for you, moving the pointer between the two clicks, a worn or dirty switch, or a software/driver conflict. Slow down the double-click speed in your mouse settings, keep the cursor still while clicking, and test the button here. If the tool shows missed or inconsistent clicks, the switch or cable may be faulty and the mouse may need repair or replacement.</p>"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

  <section
    class="max-w-[1200px] w-full mx-auto px-4 py-3 sm:py-6 flex flex-col gap-3 sm:gap-4 animate-fade-in-up pb-16 print:p-0"
