  <!-- SEO Content Article -->
  <section
    class="max-w-[760px] w-full mx-auto px-4 pb-20 flex flex-col gap-8 text-slate"
    aria-labelledby="about-tool-heading"
  >
    <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h2
        id="about-tool-heading"
        class="font-display font-semibold text-xl sm:text-2xl text-primary tracking-tight"
      >
        Free Online Double Click Test
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        This <strong>double click test</strong> is a fast, free, and private way
        to check whether your mouse is registering clicks correctly. If your
        mouse has started opening files by itself, dragging when you meant to
        click once, or firing two clicks from a single press, this
        <strong>mouse double click test</strong> will tell you exactly what is
        happening. Every click is measured in real time, so you get precise
        millisecond intervals between presses and an instant verdict on whether
        your switches are healthy or chattering. As a fully client-side
        <strong>double click test online</strong>, all measurements happen in
        your browser &mdash; nothing is uploaded, making it a genuinely private
        <strong>mouse double click test website</strong> you can use on any
        computer.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        The most common reason people reach for a
        <strong>double click test mouse</strong> tool is switch chatter. Inside
        every mechanical mouse button is a tiny metal switch. Over time the
        metal contact loses tension or collects microscopic debris, and instead
        of making one clean connection it bounces &mdash; sending two or more
        signals from a single physical press. Your computer then interprets that
        as an accidental double click. This
        <strong>double click tester</strong> catches those bounce events by
        timing the gap between clicks: intentional human double clicks rarely
        fall under 80ms, while hardware chatter typically registers in the 5ms
        to 50ms range.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        How to Use This Double Click Test
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Using the tool takes seconds. Click inside the large test area with the
        button you want to check &mdash; left, right, or the middle scroll-wheel
        button are all supported, and the browser context menu is disabled so
        right clicks register cleanly. Each press appears in the interval log
        with a precise timestamp and the gap since your previous click. If a
        click arrives faster than the chatter threshold, it is highlighted in
        red and counted as a chatter event. Watch the live counters for total
        clicks, chatter events, and chatter rate, then review the session
        summary for a per-button breakdown and an overall health verdict. You
        can export the full log as a CSV file for record keeping or warranty
        claims.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Adjustable Chatter Threshold
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Not every mouse behaves the same, so the tool lets you set the chatter
        threshold anywhere from 5ms to 150ms. A threshold of 50&ndash;80ms works
        well for most people: if a single physical click produces intervals
        below that window, your switch almost certainly has a hardware fault.
        Lowering the threshold makes the test stricter, which is useful for
        confirming borderline cases, while raising it helps you understand your
        natural clicking rhythm. This flexibility makes the tool useful both as
        a diagnostic <strong>double click</strong> checker and as a way to
        practise controlled, deliberate clicking.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Mouse and Keyboard Double Click Testing
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        While this page is primarily a <strong>mouse double click test</strong>,
        the same principle applies to any input device. A
        <strong>keyboard double click test</strong> looks for the equivalent
        problem on keys &mdash; a single keypress that registers twice because
        of contact bounce. The underlying diagnosis is identical: measure the
        interval between repeated signals and flag anything suspiciously fast.
        If you suspect a specific mouse button is failing, use the filter tabs to
        isolate the left, middle, or right button and run a focused test on just
        that switch.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        How to Double Click Correctly
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        If you are learning <strong>how to double click</strong>, the technique
