        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">
          1. What is Mouse Switch Chatter?
        </h4>
        <p>
          As mechanical mouse switches age, their internal metal leaf spring degrades, losing tension or building up corrosion. When pressed or released, the metal contact points can bounce/chatter rapidly instead of making a single clean connection. This results in the computer receiving two or more clicks within an extremely short window (typically under 50-80ms), causing accidental double-clicks.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">2. How this Tool Works</h4>
        <p>
          This test measures the precise millisecond interval between consecutive clicks. If the delay is abnormally short (below the threshold you configure), it is flagged as hardware switch chatter. Intentional rapid double-clicks by a human rarely fall below 80ms, whereas hardware bounce events typically register in the 5ms to 50ms range.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">3. Recommended Settings</h4>
        <p>
          We recommend setting the chatter threshold between 50ms and 80ms. If you observe click intervals consistently within this window during a single physical click, your mouse switch likely has hardware issues.
        </p>
